 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 251<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/23/03 3:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=348.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/bioh.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  SG3</span><hr size=1> What we purpose is not bunk, but there are serious technical and political barriers to a nuclear launch. Personally I favor a nuclear ground launch, but I am in the minority even here.<br>
<br>
Okay, your idea for a nuclear space plane is enthusiastic, but fundamentally flawed. Nuclear is only good for moving huge amounts – it would be a waste to use it just to put seven or so people into orbit. Also a plane is a relatively light thing; a HLV is an entirely different creature. <br>
<br>
Currently the biggest impediment to nuclear spacecraft is political, and it is there that we must work. Even the launch of a penny-sized piece of plutonium sends the eco-wackies into a protest orgy. If all the leaders of our countries see is that, then they will not fund or support the nuclear initiative. The best way you can help is by letting your Senators (both of them) and your Representative in congress (if you are in the US.) know you support the use of nuclear power in space.<br>
<br>
And I must disagree with Yale on Orion being illegal – space based nuclear weapons are illegal, but technically the pulse units are not weapons. They are designed much like nuclear weapons, and they could be used as such; but their primary usage is propulsion and I believe there is no prohibition against using nuclear propulsion. If you try to launch one I am certain you would be condemned, and the UN would never approve of such a thing; but you could certainly make the argument it is legal.<br>
<br>
As for the space elevator, I will not count on it until it is running. I hope it works but I am a skeptic and a cynic. I would rather have options; counting one system that hasn’t been built or proven yet (I know, this applies to nuclear to) is foolish and naïve. Besides I guarantee it will come with a host of unforeseen problems. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Dr. Carstairs </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=spaceguy3>SpaceGuy3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/23/03 8:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=348.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Thanks</span><hr size=1> Thank you all, the arguments presented on this post have convinced me of the following:<br>
<br>
1) Nuclear is not viable as a ground launch device, no matter the size because of risk (primarily) and the weight of shielding.<br>
<br>
2) The cost to get into space is incredibly high - even for a nuclear lauch capability, the cost would still be very high per pound due to the absolute demand of the public to have a fail safe system.  This would add cost and make it unfeasible.<br>
<br>
3) Therefore, I think we should focus on technologies that get humans into space as safely and cheaply as we can - this probably occurs by going back to an Apollo style capsule, or creating something like the Russian Soyuz.  Im not sure at this point if reusable really is cheaper - the Russians claim they can launch 3 people in a Soyuz for under $30 million.  Maybe we should limit human launchers to just that - human cargo and enough cargo capacity to carry up their supplies.  It currently costs about $500 million to launch the reusable space shuttle.  Big difference there in cost.<br>
<br>
4) Build a pure cargo ship to get large amounts of material to LEO.  What about using the Space Shuttle propulsion system, but instead of the Shuttle on the back of the main tank, would be a large cargo pod?  The fixed hardware costs of launching a Space Shuttle are about $50 to $60 million per launch, so the hardware costs would not be prohibitive and the infrastructure to support this type of launch already exists.  That way, we could put 200,000 pounds into LEO for about $300 a pound on a fixed cost basis.  The variable costs would probably raise that to $1000 a pound, but thats still better than $10,000 a pound that it costs now.<br>
<br>
5) Support NASA's current nuclear initiative - Prometheus - for nuclear propulsion in space - to get us to Mars and the other planets.<br>
<br>
6) Fund long term research into safely achieving a percentage of light speed travel for travel to the stars.  Maybe nuclear helps here?<br>
<br>
I just do not think a nuclear launcher would ever get off the ground, so to speak, politically, or figuratively.  Therefore, I think it wise to focus our efforts and support on programs that will get off the ground.  Calling our Senators and Congressmen to support nuclear launchers will not do any good.<br>
<br>
Those are my thoughts - thank you all for helping me to clarify the logic of this argument. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1314<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/23/03 8:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=348.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Thanks</span><hr size=1> DL wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>BAH HUMBUG its impossible I tell you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Please don't get me wrong. I most certainly <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>DO NOT</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> think that closed GCNRs are impossible. It is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>ONLY</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, repeat <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>ONLY</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>SPECIFIC</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> design details of the specific booster in the link.<br>
<br>
Months ago I spent a considerable amount of time in quite lengthy (for me) posts detailing the severe inconsistancies OF THE SPECIFIC DESIGN, while having the respondant engage in massive &quot;special pleading&quot; and various other games. It was quite frustrating.<br>
<br>
 However, beyond the issues of that specific design, and more to the general point of flying fissioning reactors thru the air, he absolutely refused to concede that his rocket was vulnerable to any of the zillion non-nuclear &quot;normal&quot; hazards of rocket launches, such as structural failure, software glitches, human error, whatever. Any of the infinite &quot;ordinary&quot; failures would drop glass reactors sizzzling with gaseous fission products into the biosphere.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
DrC wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As for the space elevator, I will not count on it until it is running. I hope it works but I am a skeptic and a cynic. I would rather have options; counting one system that hasn’t been built or proven yet (I know, this applies to nuclear to) is foolish and naïve. Besides I guarantee it will come with a host of unforeseen problems.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I certainly agree on the technical risk. That is why I wrote: <br>
<br>
&quot;In the same time period it would take to design, test, and create a nuclear booster (and then not be able to use it) a space elevator <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>may be possible</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">In any event, combustion based systems can and will do the job</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.&quot;<br>
<br>
DrC wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And I must disagree with Yale on Orion being illegal – space based nuclear weapons are illegal, but technically the pulse units are not weapons. They are designed much like nuclear weapons, and they could be used as such; but their primary usage is propulsion and I believe there is no prohibition against using nuclear propulsion. If you try to launch one I am certain you would be condemned, and the UN would never approve of such a thing; but you could certainly make the argument it is legal.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is from the text of the 1963 Limited Test Ban Treaty:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>TREATY BANNING NUCLEAR WEAPON TESTS IN THE <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">ATMOSPHERE</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->, IN <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">OUTER SPACE</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> AND UNDER WATER<br>
<br>
-------------------------------------------<br>
Signed at Moscow August 5, 1963<br>
Ratification advised by U.S. Senate September 24, 1963<br>
Ratified by U.S. President October 7, 1963<br>
U.S. ratification deposited at Washington, London, and Moscow October 10, 1963<br>
Proclaimed by U.S. President October 10, 1963<br>
Entered into force October 10, 1963<br>
...<br>
... Seeking to achieve the discontinuance of all test explosions of nuclear weapons for all time, ... and desiring to put an end to the contamination of mans environment by radioactive substances,<br>
<br>
Have agreed as follows:<br>
<br>
Article I<br>
1. Each of the Parties to this Treaty undertakes to prohibit, to prevent, and not to carry out any nuclear weapon test explosion, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">or any other nuclear explosion</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, at any place under its jurisdiction or control:<br>
<br>
(a) <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">in the atmosphere; beyond its limits, including outer space</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->; or under water, including territorial waters or high seas; or<br>
<br>
(b) <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">in any other environment if such explosion causes radioactive debris to be present outside the territorial limits of the State under whose jurisdiction or control such explosion is conducted</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->. <br>
<br>
2. Each of the Parties to this Treaty undertakes furthermore to refrain from causing, encouraging, or in any way participating in, the carrying out of any nuclear weapon test explosion, <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">or any other nuclear explosion</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->, anywhere which would take place in any of the environments described, or have the effect referred to, in paragraph 1 of this Article.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The treaty reference you seem to be referring to DrC is the 1967 Outer Space Treaty which bans the PLACING of nuclear devices in space. It is secondary to, and trumped by, the 1963 Treaty which bans <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">DETONATING</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> a nuclear device anywhere above ground (the language quite specifically, and deliberately, does not limit itself to &quot;weapons&quot;.) It is THIS treaty that makes Orion illegal. <br>
<br>
This is from the US State department's treaty &quot;Narrative&quot; which accompanied the text for the as yet un-ratified CTBT treaty, but also applies to the functioning LTBT:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>...<br>
 Nuclear Explosions for Peaceful Purposes<br>
<br>
During the negotiation of the LTBT, the phrase &quot;<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>or any other nuclear explosion&quot; was included for the specific purpose of prohibiting explosions of nuclear devices for peaceful applications, so-called &quot;peaceful nuclear explosions&quot; or &quot;PNEs</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.&quot;</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> LTBT negotiators recognized that any nuclear explosion could provide military benefits, and therefore that without the inclusion of this phrase, a State Party could conduct nuclear explosions providing valuable military benefits on the pretense that they were solely peaceful purposes explosions and not &quot;nuclear weapon test explosions.&quot;<br>
<br>
All delegations, after careful consideration, ultimately accepted the inclusion of the phrase &quot;or any other nuclear explosion&quot; in Article I of the Treaty, recognizing that PNEs would be prohibited.<br>
.....<br>
Activities Not Affected By The Treaty<br>
....<br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;"> It is important to emphasize that Article I prohibits only nuclear explosions, not all activities involving a release of nuclear energy</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Neither the 1963 LTBT nor the 1967 OST prohibit nuclear propulsion - ONLY technologies like Orion that use nuclear EXPLOSIONS.<br>
<br>
